<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-12-23T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-12-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="698" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d698">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">711.415 Traders/3</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Under Secretary of State</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Cotton</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the British Ambassador</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Lindsay</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-12-23">December 23, 1930</date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Ambassador</hi>: Referring to your note
                            of the nineteenth I should be very glad to consider such a draft as you
                            mention in that note in regard to the Australian matter, with the idea
                            that the draft should be completed promptly. I assume that your
                            Australians have a draft in mind of what they want to accomplish, and
                            that the first draft of the draft will come from you.</p>
                        <p>Sincerely yours,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">J. P. Cotton</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>